<subSubSection id="FFFA652AFFC9FFCF61E1FA07FC049DF3" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="B75F36A1FFC9FFCF61E1FA07FD729871" blockId="7.[220,700,1514,1538]" box="[220,700,1514,1538]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">
<heading id="EC1781CDFFC9FFCF61E1FA07FD729871" bold="true" box="[220,700,1514,1538]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" reason="2">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF61E1FA07FD729871" bold="true" box="[220,700,1514,1538]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF61E1FA07FEED9871" box="[220,291,1514,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Achilidae" genus="Abas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">ABAs</taxonomicName>
that increase the extent of control
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B75F36A1FFC9FFCF61A2F9CBFC049DF3" blockId="7.[159,762,1574,1948]" lastBlockId="7.[826,1429,311,1288]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">
At times 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF6032F9CBFE9A984D" box="[271,340,1574,1598]" class="Insecta" family="Achilidae" genus="Abas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">ABAs</taxonomicName>
alone cannot reduce pest numbers to below their economic injury levels and other natural enemies help to attain that goal. Control of the stored food beetle pest 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF631AF962FEB298B9" authority="Linnaeus" authorityName="Linnaeus" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Oryzaephilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="surinamensis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF631AF962FECD98B9" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Oryzaephilus surinamensis</emphasis>
Linnaeus
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF60ACF95FFDDE98B9" authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1837" box="[401,528,1714,1738]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Silvanidae</taxonomicName>
), by 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF636BF95FFE9E989E" authority="(Schrank)" baseAuthorityName="Schrank" baseAuthorityYear="1781" class="Arachnida" family="Cheyletidae" genus="Cheyletus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eruditus">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF636BF95FFF18989E" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Cheyletus eruditus</emphasis>
(Schrank)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF605FF938FE3F989E" authorityName="W.E.Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[354,497,1749,1773]" class="Arachnida" family="Cheyletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheyletidae</taxonomicName>
) was improved when the hymenopterous parasitoid 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF6331F915FEEC9940" authority="(Ashmead)" baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1893" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Cephalonomia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarsalis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF6331F915FD379963" box="[524,761,1784,1808]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Cephalonomia tarsalis</emphasis>
(Ashmead)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF600AF8F6FE799940" box="[311,439,1819,1843]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bethylidae</taxonomicName>
) was introduced into the food bin (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF6027F8D3FDED9924" author="Zdarkova E. &amp; Lukas J. &amp; Horak P." box="[282,547,1854,1880]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="29 - 34" refId="ref22887" refString="Zdarkova E., Lukas J., Horak P. 2003 - Compatibility of Cheyletus eruditus (Schrank) (Acari: Cheyletidae) and Cephalonomia tarsalis (Ashmead) (Hymenoptera: Bethylidae) in biological control of stored grain pests - Plant Prot. Sci., 38: 29 - 34." type="journal article" year="2003">
Å½darkova 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF60A7F8D2FE1D9925" box="[410,467,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">et al.</emphasis>
2003
</bibRefCitation>
). Another group of natural enemies are nematodes. The release of 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF61A2F869FDD899EF" authority="(Canestrini)" baseAuthorityName="Canestrini" box="[159,534,1924,1948]" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Gaeolaelaps" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aculeifer">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF61A2F869FE4F99EF" box="[159,385,1924,1948]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Gaeolaelaps aculeifer</emphasis>
(Canestrini)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF631AF869FD6499EF" authorityName="A.Berlese" authorityYear="1892" box="[551,682,1924,1948]" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Laelapidae</taxonomicName>
) (then known as 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF62FEFEDAFB539F3C" baseAuthorityName="G.Canestrini" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[963,1181,311,335]" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Hypoaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aculeifer">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF62FEFEDAFB539F3C" box="[963,1181,311,335]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Hypoaspis aculeifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) along with nematodes, significantly reduced the numbers of the WFT infesting green beans (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF65A2FE90FCBD9FCB" author="Premachandra W. T. S. D. &amp; Borgemeister C. &amp; Berndt O. &amp; Ehlers R. - U. &amp; Poehling H. - M." pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="529 - 541" refId="ref19502" refString="Premachandra W. T. S. D., Borgemeister C., Berndt O., Ehlers R. - U., Poehling H. - M. 2003 - Combined releases of entomopathogenic nematodes and the predatory mite Hypoaspis aculeifer to control soil-dwelling stages of western flower thrips Frankliniella occidentalis - BioControl, 48: 529 - 541." type="journal article" year="2003">
Premachandra 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF6467FE93FA5B9FE6" box="[1370,1429,381,405]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">et al.</emphasis>
2003
</bibRefCitation>
), as well as sciarids and phorids (
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF6416FE4DFA469FCB" box="[1323,1416,416,440]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
), pests of mushrooms in compost and casing substrates (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF62ABFE0BFB629F8D" author="Jess S. &amp; Bingham J. F. W." box="[918,1196,486,510]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="159 - 167" refId="ref15465" refString="Jess S., Bingham J. F. W. 2004 - Biological control of sciarid and phorid pests of mushroom with predatory mites from the genus Hypoaspis (Acari: Hypoaspidae) and the entomopathogenic nematode Steinernema feltiae - Bull. Entomol. Res., 94: 159 - 167." type="journal article" year="2004">Jess and Bingham 2004</bibRefCitation>
). The predatory cecidomyiid 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF6282FDE4FAD39C52" authority="(Kieffer)" baseAuthorityName="Kieffer" box="[959,1309,521,545]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Therodiplosis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persicae">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF6282FDE4FB619C52" box="[959,1199,521,545]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Therodiplosis persicae</emphasis>
(Kieffer)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF640CFDE4FA429C52" box="[1329,1420,521,545]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
) &quot;supported&quot; the control of 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF65B8FDC0FB219C37" authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1836" box="[1157,1263,557,580]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetranychidae" genus="Tetranychus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urticae">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF65B8FDC0FB219C37" box="[1157,1263,557,580]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">T. urticae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF6419FDC0FC949C14" authorityName="Athias-Henriot" authorityYear="1957" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Phytoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persimilis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF6419FDC0FC949C14" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">P. persimilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on tomatoes in a greenhouse (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF65FCFDA2FA9B9C14" author="Fiedler Z." box="[1217,1365,591,615]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="650 - 654" refId="ref13618" refString="Fiedler Z. 2005 - A predatory midge Therodiplosis persicae a factor supporting effectiveness of Phytoseiulus persimilis (Athias-Henriot) in reduction of Tetranychus urticae (Koch) on tomato plants in the greenhouse - Prog. Plant Prot., 45: 650 - 654." type="journal article" year="2005">Fiedler 2005</bibRefCitation>
), and the generalist ant 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF6531FD9EFA919CF8" authority="Mayr" authorityName="Mayr" box="[1036,1375,627,651]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pristomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF6531FD9EFAD69CF9" box="[1036,1304,627,650]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Pristomyrmex punctatus</emphasis>
Mayr
</taxonomicName>
&quot;enhanced&quot; the control of the spider mite 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF642CFD78FBCA9CA3" authority="Kishida" authorityName="Kishida" authorityYear="1927" class="Arachnida" family="Tetranychidae" genus="Tetranychus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanzawai">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF642CFD78FC509CA3" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Tetranychus kanzawai</emphasis>
Kishida
</taxonomicName>
by 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF650AFD55FB809C87" authority="Schicha (Otsuki and Yano 2014)" authorityName="Schicha (Otsuki and Yano" authorityYear="2014" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="womersleyi">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF650AFD55FAFE9CA3" box="[1079,1328,696,720]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Neoseiulus womersleyi</emphasis>
Schicha (
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF627FFD31FB889C87" author="Otsuki H. &amp; Yano S." box="[834,1094,732,756]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="27 - 33" refId="ref18711" refString="Otsuki H., Yano S. 2014 - Functionally different predators break down antipredator defenses of spider mites - Entomol. Exp. Appl., 151: 27 - 33." type="journal article" year="2014">Otsuki and Yano 2014</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The greatest damage to the leaf surface area of water hyacinth occurred when the Hemipteran 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF653EFCCFFA5B9D49" authority="(Carvalho)" baseAuthorityName="Carvalho" box="[1027,1429,802,826]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Eccritotarsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catarinens">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF653EFCCFFAC59D4A" box="[1027,1291,802,825]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">Eccritotarsus catarinens</emphasis>
(Carvalho)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF627FFCA8FC6F9D2E" box="[834,929,837,861]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Miridae</taxonomicName>
) was used along with 
<taxonomicName id="70E04D22FFC9FFCF659EFCA8FC089DF3" authority="(Marlin et al. 2013 b)" baseAuthorityName="Marlin" baseAuthorityYear="2013" class="Arachnida" family="Galumnidae" genus="Orthogalumna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terebrantis">
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF659EFCA8FAF89D2E" box="[1187,1334,837,861]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">O. terebrantis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF6479FCA8FC709DF3" author="Marlin D. &amp; Hill M. P. &amp; Byrne M. J." pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="483 - 490" refId="ref17480" refString="Marlin D., Hill M. P., Byrne M. J. 2013 b - Interactions within pairs of biological control agents on water hyacinth, Eichhornia crassipes - Biol. Control., 67: 483 - 490. doi: 10.1016 / j. biocontrol. 2013.10.006" type="journal article" year="2013">
Marlin 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF6207FC84FCA09DF3" box="[826,878,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">et al.</emphasis>
2013b
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FFFA652AFFC9FFCF625DFC7CFBE59B7B" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" type="description">
<paragraph id="B75F36A1FFC9FFCF625DFC7CFBE59B7B" blockId="7.[826,1429,311,1288]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">
Such results are generally consistent with the opinions of 
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF62F8FC59FAE89DBF" author="Stiling P. &amp; Cornelissen T." box="[965,1318,948,972]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="236 - 246" refId="ref21388" refString="Stiling P., Cornelissen T. 2005 - What makes a successful biocontrol agent? A meta-analysis of biological control agent performance - Biol. Control, 34: 236 - 246. doi: 10.1016 / j. biocontrol. 2005.02.017" type="journal article" year="2005">Stiling and Cornelissen (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, who calculated that the addition of two or more biocontrol agents, especially if generalists, increased pest mortality by 13 %, decreasing pest abundance by 27.2 %, as compared to single releases or when BC agents were specialists. This may be explained by the ability of generalists to survive on the crop when the numbers of the target-pest are much reduced, and will thus be in place if the pest resurges (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="D3714B50FFC9FFCF6207FB02FBEE9B7B" author="Palevsky E. &amp; Gerson U. &amp; Zhang Z. - Q." box="[826,1056,1263,1288]" pageId="7" pageNumber="377" pagination="11 - 26" refId="ref18751" refString="Palevsky E., Gerson U., Zhang Z. - Q. 2013 - Can exotic phytoseiids be considered ' benevolent invaders' in perennial cropping systems? - Exp. Appl. Acarol., 59: 11 - 26. doi: 10.1007 / s 10493 - 012 - 9575 - 4" type="journal article" year="2013">
Palevsky 
<emphasis id="8594EAB3FFC9FFCF6297FB1DFC109B74" box="[938,990,1263,1287]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="377">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
